snippet.textDisplay:
Simply amazing--a near perfect song, a great fusion of three threads i.e. Punjab folk and Indo-Pakistani semi-classical and modern rock.  Each thread or stage is marked by a subtle transition, first with the opening leading up to the Sagar-Veena and the Shilpa Ji's vocals ushering in the final rock outburst. Yet, all the three stages/phases are boung together and united by the common motifs of the traditional Sohni-Mahinwal Punjabi folk tale and the mystic Sufi element whereby the 'kacha' gharra' (the fragile clay vessel) can be transcended , via the guidance of the spiritual 'Pakka Murshid'' (true teacher). The fragile clay vessel, thus can be seen as more than just a utensil but actually may be seen as a metaphor for humanity, human beings, each of us clay vessels and subject to the ego. I am reminded by this lovely and deeply meaningful song, of the contemporary poetry of famous Pakistani mystic-poet Omar Tarin, who writes (1992) 
''The Pitcher

We could see it sailing by
Bobbing on the stream,
Polished to a rotund gleam
By its wayfaring ablutions.
Only for a second, some slim
Brown hand
Must have relinquished its 
Hold to the waters,
Watching in dismay
The self-willed lustre
Of Potter’s Clay.''
